{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":276,"text":"I want to talk to you today about something"},{"time":2221,"text":"the open-source programming world can teach democracy,"},{"time":5236,"text":"but before that, a little preamble."},{"time":6871,"text":"Let's start here."}]},{"cues":[{"time":8691,"text":"This is Martha Payne. Martha's a 9-year-old Scot"},{"time":12086,"text":"who lives in the Council of Argyll and Bute."},{"time":14107,"text":"A couple months ago, Payne started a food blog"},{"time":16800,"text":"called NeverSeconds, and she would take her camera"},{"time":19673,"text":"with her every day to school to document"},{"time":21953,"text":"her school lunches."},{"time":23967,"text":"Can you spot the vegetable? (Laughter)"},{"time":25856,"text":"And, as sometimes happens,"},{"time":29610,"text":"this blog acquired first dozens of readers,"},{"time":32200,"text":"and then hundreds of readers,"},{"time":33880,"text":"and then thousands of readers, as people tuned in"},{"time":36466,"text":"to watch her rate her school lunches,"},{"time":38134,"text":"including on my favorite category,"},{"time":39659,"text":"\"Pieces of hair found in food.\" (Laughter)"},{"time":43251,"text":"This was a zero day. That's good."}]},{"cues":[{"time":46722,"text":"And then two weeks ago yesterday, she posted this."},{"time":49916,"text":"A post that read: \"Goodbye.\""},{"time":51827,"text":"And she said, \"I'm very sorry to tell you this, but"},{"time":55041,"text":"my head teacher pulled me out of class today and told me"},{"time":57785,"text":"I'm not allowed to take pictures in the lunch room anymore."},{"time":60781,"text":"I really enjoyed doing this."},{"time":62507,"text":"Thank you for reading. Goodbye.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":65737,"text":"You can guess what happened next, right? (Laughter)"},{"time":70915,"text":"The outrage was so swift, so voluminous, so unanimous,"},{"time":76833,"text":"that the Council of Argyll and Bute reversed themselves"},{"time":79779,"text":"the same day and said, \"We would,"},{"time":81065,"text":"we would never censor a nine-year-old.\" (Laughter)"},{"time":83231,"text":"Except, of course, this morning. (Laughter)"},{"time":85708,"text":"And this brings up the question,"},{"time":90121,"text":"what made them think they could get away"},{"time":92335,"text":"with something like that? (Laughter)"},{"time":94385,"text":"And the answer is, all of human history prior to now."}]},{"cues":[{"time":99102,"text":"(Laughter) So,"},{"time":102650,"text":"what happens when a medium suddenly puts"},{"time":106575,"text":"a lot of new ideas into circulation?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":110279,"text":"Now, this isn't just a contemporaneous question."},{"time":112384,"text":"This is something we've faced several times"},{"time":114384,"text":"over the last few centuries."},{"time":115740,"text":"When the telegraph came along, it was clear"},{"time":117725,"text":"that it was going to globalize the news industry."},{"time":119943,"text":"What would this lead to?"},{"time":121432,"text":"Well, obviously, it would lead to world peace."},{"time":124996,"text":"The television, a medium that allowed us not just to hear"},{"time":127806,"text":"but see, literally see, what was going on"},{"time":130573,"text":"elsewhere in the world, what would this lead to?"},{"time":132890,"text":"World peace. (Laughter)"},{"time":135130,"text":"The telephone?"},{"time":136087,"text":"You guessed it: world peace."},{"time":138682,"text":"Sorry for the spoiler alert, but no world peace. Not yet."},{"time":143656,"text":"Even the printing press, even the printing press"},{"time":146135,"text":"was assumed to be a tool that was going to enforce"},{"time":149264,"text":"Catholic intellectual hegemony across Europe."},{"time":152917,"text":"Instead, what we got was Martin Luther's 95 Theses,"},{"time":155401,"text":"the Protestant Reformation, and, you know,"},{"time":157421,"text":"the Thirty Years' War. All right,"},{"time":159779,"text":"so what all of these predictions of world peace got right"},{"time":164010,"text":"is that when a lot of new ideas suddenly"},{"time":166541,"text":"come into circulation, it changes society."},{"time":169467,"text":"What they got exactly wrong was what happens next."}]},{"cues":[{"time":172999,"text":"The more ideas there are in circulation,"},{"time":175548,"text":"the more ideas there are for any individual to disagree with."},{"time":180256,"text":"More media always means more arguing."},{"time":185029,"text":"That's what happens when the media's space expands."},{"time":187949,"text":"And yet, when we look back on the printing press"},{"time":190852,"text":"in the early years, we like what happened."},{"time":194231,"text":"We are a pro-printing press society."}]},{"cues":[{"time":197475,"text":"So how do we square those two things,"},{"time":199445,"text":"that it leads to more arguing, but we think it was good?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":202201,"text":"And the answer, I think, can be found in things like this."},{"time":204800,"text":"This is the cover of \"Philosophical Transactions,\""},{"time":208085,"text":"the first scientific journal ever published in English"},{"time":210707,"text":"in the middle of the 1600s,"},{"time":212589,"text":"and it was created by a group of people who had been"},{"time":214416,"text":"calling themselves \"The Invisible College,\""},{"time":216053,"text":"a group of natural philosophers who only later"},{"time":218257,"text":"would call themselves scientists,"},{"time":220862,"text":"and they wanted to improve the way"},{"time":224406,"text":"natural philosophers argued with each other,"},{"time":227063,"text":"and they needed to do two things for this."},{"time":229053,"text":"They needed openness. They needed to create a norm"},{"time":231537,"text":"which said, when you do an experiment,"},{"time":233396,"text":"you have to publish not just your claims,"},{"time":236081,"text":"but how you did the experiment."},{"time":237507,"text":"If you don't tell us how you did it, we won't trust you."},{"time":240304,"text":"But the other thing they needed was speed."},{"time":242664,"text":"They had to quickly synchronize what"},{"time":244969,"text":"other natural philosophers knew. Otherwise,"},{"time":247423,"text":"you couldn't get the right kind of argument going."},{"time":250280,"text":"The printing press was clearly the right medium for this,"},{"time":253230,"text":"but the book was the wrong tool. It was too slow."},{"time":255816,"text":"And so they invented the scientific journal"},{"time":258678,"text":"as a way of synchronizing the argument"},{"time":261464,"text":"across the community of natural scientists."},{"time":264018,"text":"The scientific revolution wasn't created by the printing press."},{"time":267516,"text":"It was created by scientists,"},{"time":269662,"text":"but it couldn't have been created if they didn't have"},{"time":271521,"text":"a printing press as a tool."}]},{"cues":[{"time":273691,"text":"So what about us? What about our generation,"},{"time":275931,"text":"and our media revolution, the Internet?"},{"time":277934,"text":"Well, predictions of world peace? Check. (Laughter)"},{"time":282053,"text":"More arguing? Gold star on that one. (Laughter)"},{"time":290636,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":291947,"text":"I mean, YouTube is just a gold mine. (Laughter)"},{"time":296294,"text":"Better arguing? That's the question."}]},{"cues":[{"time":300389,"text":"So I study social media, which means,"},{"time":302433,"text":"to a first approximation, I watch people argue."},{"time":305044,"text":"And if I had to pick a group that I think is"},{"time":309151,"text":"our Invisible College, is our generation's collection of people"},{"time":312944,"text":"trying to take these tools and to press it into service,"},{"time":316103,"text":"not for more arguments, but for better arguments,"},{"time":318884,"text":"I'd pick the open-source programmers."},{"time":321279,"text":"Programming is a three-way relationship"},{"time":323541,"text":"between a programmer, some source code,"},{"time":325825,"text":"and the computer it's meant to run on, but computers"},{"time":328439,"text":"are such famously inflexible interpreters of instructions"},{"time":333141,"text":"that it's extraordinarily difficult to write out a set"},{"time":337164,"text":"of instructions that the computer knows how to execute,"},{"time":340202,"text":"and that's if one person is writing it."},{"time":342068,"text":"Once you get more than one person writing it,"},{"time":344167,"text":"it's very easy for any two programmers to overwrite"},{"time":347251,"text":"each other's work if they're working on the same file,"},{"time":349912,"text":"or to send incompatible instructions"},{"time":352094,"text":"that simply causes the computer to choke,"},{"time":354535,"text":"and this problem grows larger"},{"time":357494,"text":"the more programmers are involved."},{"time":360263,"text":"To a first approximation, the problem of managing"},{"time":363610,"text":"a large software project is the problem"},{"time":366336,"text":"of keeping this social chaos at bay."}]},{"cues":[{"time":369992,"text":"Now, for decades there has been a canonical solution"},{"time":372467,"text":"to this problem, which is to use something called"},{"time":374121,"text":"a \"version control system,\""},{"time":376101,"text":"and a version control system does what is says on the tin."},{"time":378310,"text":"It provides a canonical copy of the software"},{"time":381704,"text":"on a server somewhere."},{"time":383256,"text":"The only programmers who can change it are people"},{"time":386162,"text":"who've specifically been given permission to access it,"},{"time":389693,"text":"and they're only allowed to access the sub-section of it"},{"time":393460,"text":"that they have permission to change."},{"time":395890,"text":"And when people draw diagrams of version control systems,"},{"time":399075,"text":"the diagrams always look something like this."},{"time":401440,"text":"All right. They look like org charts."},{"time":404318,"text":"And you don't have to squint very hard"},{"time":405725,"text":"to see the political ramifications of a system like this."},{"time":409190,"text":"This is feudalism: one owner, many workers."}]},{"cues":[{"time":413666,"text":"Now, that's fine for the commercial software industry."},{"time":416990,"text":"It really is Microsoft's Office. It's Adobe's Photoshop."},{"time":422380,"text":"The corporation owns the software."},{"time":425212,"text":"The programmers come and go."}]},{"cues":[{"time":427526,"text":"But there was one programmer who decided"},{"time":430899,"text":"that this wasn't the way to work."},{"time":433887,"text":"This is Linus Torvalds."},{"time":435149,"text":"Torvalds is the most famous open-source programmer,"},{"time":437301,"text":"created Linux, obviously, and Torvalds looked at the way"},{"time":442602,"text":"the open-source movement had been dealing with this problem."},{"time":446114,"text":"Open-source software, the core promise of the open-source license,"},{"time":450738,"text":"is that everybody should have access to all the source code"},{"time":454484,"text":"all the time, but of course, this creates"},{"time":457737,"text":"the very threat of chaos you have to forestall"},{"time":461044,"text":"in order to get anything working."},{"time":462622,"text":"So most open-source projects just held their noses"},{"time":465104,"text":"and adopted the feudal management systems."}]},{"cues":[{"time":467784,"text":"But Torvalds said, \"No, I'm not going to do that.\""},{"time":470292,"text":"His point of view on this was very clear."},{"time":473857,"text":"When you adopt a tool, you also adopt"},{"time":476390,"text":"the management philosophy embedded in that tool,"},{"time":479979,"text":"and he wasn't going to adopt anything that didn't work"},{"time":483115,"text":"the way the Linux community worked."},{"time":485424,"text":"And to give you a sense of how enormous"},{"time":487956,"text":"a decision like this was, this is a map"},{"time":491624,"text":"of the internal dependencies within Linux,"},{"time":495113,"text":"within the Linux operating system, which sub-parts"},{"time":497720,"text":"of the program rely on which other sub-parts to get going."},{"time":502165,"text":"This is a tremendously complicated process."},{"time":505743,"text":"This is a tremendously complicated program,"},{"time":508535,"text":"and yet, for years, Torvalds ran this"},{"time":511200,"text":"not with automated tools but out of his email box."},{"time":515104,"text":"People would literally mail him changes"},{"time":517577,"text":"that they'd agreed on, and he would merge them by hand."}]},{"cues":[{"time":521696,"text":"And then, 15 years after looking at Linux and figuring out"},{"time":526442,"text":"how the community worked, he said, \"I think I know"},{"time":529252,"text":"how to write a version control system for free people.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":533419,"text":"And he called it \"Git.\" Git is distributed version control."},{"time":539314,"text":"It has two big differences"},{"time":542338,"text":"with traditional version control systems."},{"time":544401,"text":"The first is that it lives up to the philosophical promise"},{"time":547548,"text":"of open-source. Everybody who works on a project"},{"time":550834,"text":"has access to all of the source code all of the time."},{"time":554505,"text":"And when people draw diagrams of Git workflow,"},{"time":557179,"text":"they use drawings that look like this."},{"time":560116,"text":"And you don't have to understand what the circles"},{"time":562434,"text":"and boxes and arrows mean to see that this is a far more"},{"time":566113,"text":"complicated way of working than is supported"},{"time":569208,"text":"by ordinary version control systems."}]},{"cues":[{"time":571929,"text":"But this is also the thing that brings the chaos back,"},{"time":576238,"text":"and this is Git's second big innovation."},{"time":579288,"text":"This is a screenshot from GitHub, the premier Git hosting service,"},{"time":583284,"text":"and every time a programmer uses Git"},{"time":586634,"text":"to make any important change at all,"},{"time":589795,"text":"creating a new file, modifying an existing one,"},{"time":593104,"text":"merging two files, Git creates this kind of signature."},{"time":597778,"text":"This long string of numbers and letters here"},{"time":600921,"text":"is a unique identifier tied to every single change,"},{"time":605996,"text":"but without any central coordination."},{"time":608853,"text":"Every Git system generates this number the same way,"},{"time":613342,"text":"which means this is a signature tied directly"},{"time":616684,"text":"and unforgeably to a particular change."}]},{"cues":[{"time":619834,"text":"This has the following effect:"},{"time":621770,"text":"A programmer in Edinburgh and a programmer in Entebbe"},{"time":625448,"text":"can both get the same -- a copy of the same piece of software."},{"time":629150,"text":"Each of them can make changes and they can merge them"},{"time":632976,"text":"after the fact even if they didn't know"},{"time":635911,"text":"of each other's existence beforehand."},{"time":638870,"text":"This is cooperation without coordination."},{"time":642369,"text":"This is the big change."}]},{"cues":[{"time":645305,"text":"Now, I tell you all of this not to convince you that it's great"},{"time":650515,"text":"that open-source programmers now have a tool"},{"time":654212,"text":"that supports their philosophical way of working,"},{"time":657305,"text":"although I think that is great."},{"time":659409,"text":"I tell you all of this because of what I think it means"},{"time":662177,"text":"for the way communities come together."}]},{"cues":[{"time":664371,"text":"Once Git allowed for cooperation without coordination,"},{"time":670690,"text":"you start to see communities form"},{"time":673630,"text":"that are enormously large and complex."}]},{"cues":[{"time":677882,"text":"This is a graph of the Ruby community."},{"time":680161,"text":"It's an open-source programming language,"},{"time":681690,"text":"and all of the interconnections between the people --"},{"time":684688,"text":"this is now not a software graph, but a people graph,"},{"time":687087,"text":"all of the interconnections among the people"},{"time":689189,"text":"working on that project —"},{"time":691532,"text":"and this doesn't look like an org chart."},{"time":694522,"text":"This looks like a dis-org chart, and yet,"},{"time":697942,"text":"out of this community, but using these tools,"},{"time":700550,"text":"they can now create something together."},{"time":702836,"text":"So there are two good reasons to think that"},{"time":707201,"text":"this kind of technique can be applied"},{"time":711374,"text":"to democracies in general and in particular to the law."}]},{"cues":[{"time":715907,"text":"When you make the claim, in fact,"},{"time":717765,"text":"that something on the Internet is going to be good"},{"time":720723,"text":"for democracy, you often get this reaction."}]},{"cues":[{"time":723164,"text":"(Music) (Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":729088,"text":"Which is, are you talking about the thing"},{"time":731614,"text":"with the singing cats? Like, is that the thing"},{"time":734025,"text":"you think is going to be good for society?"},{"time":736654,"text":"To which I have to say, here's the thing"},{"time":738789,"text":"with the singing cats. That always happens."},{"time":742150,"text":"And I don't just mean that always happens with the Internet,"},{"time":743883,"text":"I mean that always happens with media, full stop."},{"time":746463,"text":"It did not take long after the rise"},{"time":748503,"text":"of the commercial printing press before someone"},{"time":751179,"text":"figured out that erotic novels were a good idea. (Laughter)"},{"time":754492,"text":"You don't have to have an economic incentive to sell books"},{"time":757534,"text":"very long before someone says, \"Hey, you know what I bet"},{"time":760555,"text":"people would pay for?\" (Laughter)"},{"time":762723,"text":"It took people another 150 years to even think"},{"time":766273,"text":"of the scientific journal, right? So -- (Laughter) (Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":773033,"text":"So the harnessing by the Invisible College"},{"time":776071,"text":"of the printing press to create the scientific journal"},{"time":778456,"text":"was phenomenally important, but it didn't happen big,"},{"time":781367,"text":"and it didn't happen quick, and it didn't happen fast, so"},{"time":784126,"text":"if you're going to look for where the change is happening,"},{"time":787424,"text":"you have to look on the margins."}]},{"cues":[{"time":789440,"text":"So, the law is also dependency-related."},{"time":794904,"text":"This is a graph of the U.S. Tax Code,"},{"time":798313,"text":"and the dependencies of one law on other laws"},{"time":801393,"text":"for the overall effect."},{"time":803791,"text":"So there's that as a site for source code management."},{"time":807223,"text":"But there's also the fact that law is another place"},{"time":809125,"text":"where there are many opinions in circulation,"},{"time":811399,"text":"but they need to be resolved to one canonical copy,"},{"time":814907,"text":"and when you go onto GitHub, and you look around,"},{"time":817484,"text":"there are millions and millions of projects,"},{"time":819553,"text":"almost all of which are source code,"},{"time":820907,"text":"but if you look around the edges, you can see people"},{"time":823592,"text":"experimenting with the political ramifications"},{"time":825801,"text":"of a system like that."},{"time":827414,"text":"Someone put up all the Wikileaked cables"},{"time":829224,"text":"from the State Department, along with software used"},{"time":831489,"text":"to interpret them, including my favorite use ever"},{"time":834678,"text":"of the Cablegate cables, which is a tool for detecting"},{"time":837049,"text":"naturally occurring haiku in State Department prose."},{"time":840064,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":845960,"text":"Right. (Laughter)"},{"time":849032,"text":"The New York Senate has put up something called"},{"time":851831,"text":"Open Legislation, also hosting it on GitHub,"},{"time":854238,"text":"again for all of the reasons of updating and fluidity."},{"time":856624,"text":"You can go and pick your Senator and then you can see"},{"time":859290,"text":"a list of bills they have sponsored."},{"time":861325,"text":"Someone going by Divegeek has put up the Utah code,"},{"time":864957,"text":"the laws of the state of Utah, and they've put it up there"},{"time":867722,"text":"not just to distribute the code,"},{"time":869171,"text":"but with the very interesting possibility that this could"},{"time":872369,"text":"be used to further the development of legislation."},{"time":876924,"text":"Somebody put up a tool during the copyright debate"},{"time":880763,"text":"last year in the Senate, saying, \"It's strange that Hollywood"},{"time":884949,"text":"has more access to Canadian legislators"},{"time":888073,"text":"than Canadian citizens do. Why don't we use GitHub"},{"time":891889,"text":"to show them what a citizen-developed bill might look like?\""},{"time":896365,"text":"And it includes this very evocative screenshot."}]},{"cues":[{"time":900117,"text":"This is a called a \"diff,\" this thing on the right here."},{"time":903095,"text":"This shows you, for text that many people are editing,"},{"time":906065,"text":"when a change was made, who made it,"},{"time":908266,"text":"and what the change is."},{"time":909269,"text":"The stuff in red is the stuff that got deleted."},{"time":910724,"text":"The stuff in green is the stuff that got added."},{"time":913416,"text":"Programmers take this capability for granted."},{"time":916198,"text":"No democracy anywhere in the world offers this feature"},{"time":919123,"text":"to its citizens for either legislation or for budgets,"},{"time":922938,"text":"even though those are the things done"},{"time":925468,"text":"with our consent and with our money."}]},{"cues":[{"time":928607,"text":"Now, I would love to tell you that the fact"},{"time":931845,"text":"that the open-source programmers have worked out"},{"time":935017,"text":"a collaborative method that is large scale, distributed,"},{"time":938688,"text":"cheap, and in sync with the ideals of democracy, I would love"},{"time":942153,"text":"to tell you that because those tools are in place,"},{"time":944324,"text":"the innovation is inevitable. But it's not."},{"time":948655,"text":"Part of the problem, of course, is just a lack of information."},{"time":951648,"text":"Somebody put a question up on Quora saying,"},{"time":953551,"text":"\"Why is it that lawmakers don't use"},{"time":955643,"text":"distributed version control?\""},{"time":957050,"text":"This, graphically, was the answer. (Laughter)"},{"time":960671,"text":"(Laughter) (Applause)"},{"time":962762,"text":"And that is indeed part of the problem, but only part."}]},{"cues":[{"time":967784,"text":"The bigger problem, of course, is power."},{"time":970961,"text":"The people experimenting with participation don't have"},{"time":974131,"text":"legislative power, and the people who have legislative"},{"time":976700,"text":"power are not experimenting with participation."},{"time":980663,"text":"They are experimenting with openness."},{"time":982208,"text":"There's no democracy worth the name that doesn't have"},{"time":984068,"text":"a transparency move, but transparency is openness"},{"time":986996,"text":"in only one direction, and being given a dashboard"},{"time":990901,"text":"without a steering wheel has never been the core promise"},{"time":994071,"text":"a democracy makes to its citizens."}]},{"cues":[{"time":997482,"text":"So consider this."},{"time":999832,"text":"The thing that got Martha Payne's opinions"},{"time":1002418,"text":"out into the public was a piece of technology,"},{"time":1006109,"text":"but the thing that kept them there was political will."},{"time":1009743,"text":"It was the expectation of the citizens"},{"time":1012017,"text":"that she would not be censored."},{"time":1015552,"text":"That's now the state we're in with these collaboration tools."},{"time":1020880,"text":"We have them. We've seen them. They work."},{"time":1024887,"text":"Can we use them?"},{"time":1025938,"text":"Can we apply the techniques that worked here to this?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1031064,"text":"T.S. Eliot once said, \"One of the most momentous things"},{"time":1034781,"text":"that can happen to a culture"},{"time":1036861,"text":"is that they acquire a new form of prose.\""},{"time":1040504,"text":"I think that's wrong, but -- (Laughter)"},{"time":1042752,"text":"I think it's right for argumentation. Right?"},{"time":1046411,"text":"A momentous thing that can happen to a culture"},{"time":1049766,"text":"is they can acquire a new style of arguing:"},{"time":1052580,"text":"trial by jury, voting, peer review, now this. Right?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1059296,"text":"A new form of arguing has been invented in our lifetimes,"},{"time":1062365,"text":"in the last decade, in fact."},{"time":1064252,"text":"It's large, it's distributed, it's low-cost,"},{"time":1068305,"text":"and it's compatible with the ideals of democracy."},{"time":1071604,"text":"The question for us now is, are we going to let"},{"time":1073590,"text":"the programmers keep it to themselves?"},{"time":1075116,"text":"Or are we going to try and take it and press it into service"},{"time":1077165,"text":"for society at large?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1079317,"text":"Thank you for listening. (Applause)"},{"time":1081917,"text":"(Applause)"},{"time":1086055,"text":"Thank you. Thank you. (Applause)"}]}]}